Anonymous Fri 09 Apr 2021 05:02:43 No.37764684 Report
Quoted By: >>37764849 >>37764895 >>37764971 >>37766930 >>37767444 >>37767478 >>37767971
>>37764007
You both underestimate humans and overestimate animals. A rabbit scaled up to human size would not be able to run at the same speed, jump the same distance, or kick as proportionally hard as a normal rabbit. That's why insects are so successful. If you scaled one up to human size it would be absolute garbage. Smaller animals have higher proportional strength. Another thing is that you're comparing wild animals to modern living people. Think about a man living all on his own in the woods with only what he can scavenge and create from them. He's going to be far stronger than the average modern man. Anthros wouldn't be magically immune to this. In a fight between an anthro and a human, pretty much everything rests on the initial moments. If the anthro manages to get its teeth or claws into a vital area then there's a good chance they win, but if they fail then there's almost no chance of recovery for them. Grabbing opens up a massive array of options for a human fighter that wouldn't be open to an anthro fighter, again, especially because fur makes grabbing all that much easier. Punching is another, perhaps surprisingly, major part. Most animals are built for fighting against other things with teeth and claws that will dig into them. Raw blunt force would be very dangerous to the head, and it would be devastating if even a single good punch were landed on the muzzle, even moreso were it head on. They very much aren't built for taking blunt strikes to the front of their muzzles. In fact, the same is true of humans. That's why getting punched right in the mouth or across the chin is something that fighters put so much effort into trying to avoid. That would only be even worse for an anthro. And unironically that would make hares perhaps one of the most dangerous anthros to humans—their cranial kinesis allows them to absorb hits to the head much better.
Tl;dr only things much larger than humans (+hares) would be able to attack us and have moderately good odds.

>>37764684
You make an interesting point about punching, but since we're talking about anthros, they're probably just as capable of it as humans since they'll have similar hands. And fur might soften blunt trauma, since it acts as soft fluff that'll absorb the blow.
As for using fur for grappling, that'll depend on the anthro in question too. Horses are furry, but their coats are so damn thin (unlike their manes, of course) that you'd never be able to grab it and hold on. Anthros often seem to be designed similarly, with the fur on their bodies being way thinner than their real-life counterparts... which makes sense, since they've evolved to be comfortable with clothes on top of it.
And the reason why creatures like chimps are way stronger than humans is because their muscles are much more dense. And I'm assuming that goes for most animal species. This could easily carry over into anthros, even if to a lesser degree, so even though anthros are the same size as humans, their muscles still pack more power.

Neat discussion, though.

>Uh, yes it does? Aren't we talking about how humans would get the snot beaten out of them by anthros in a brawl? Pretty sure that's what started this debate.
You're basing that off of "anthros would be stronger than humans because real world animals have higher proportional strength than humans." The problem with that is twofold.
